<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="section faq-section" id="faq">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
            <span class="section-label section-label-yellow">FAQ</span>
            <h2 class="section-heading">Common Questions</h2>
            <p class="section-subtext">Everything you need to know before you buy, and after.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-inner">
            <div class="faq-item active">
                <button class="faq-question">
                    <h3>How does RADCam's AI know what to say?</h3>
                    <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                </button>
                <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 500px;">
                    <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                        RADCam uses AITX's AIR™ (Autonomous Intelligent Response) technology to engage in real-time, contextual conversations. It's not scripted. The AI understands what it's seeing (a delivery, a visitor, suspicious activity) and responds accordingly. It can welcome visitors, question suspicious individuals, warn intruders, and monitor packages, all autonomously and in real time.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">
                    <h3>What kinds of alerts will I receive?</h3>
                    <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                </button>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                        RADCam filters out nuisance notifications and only sends you four types of meaningful alerts: <strong>Visitor Alerts</strong> (someone at your door who wants to speak with you or needs a signature), <strong>Security Alerts</strong> (suspicious behavior or someone who refused to leave after being warned), <strong>Package Alerts</strong> (delivery confirmed or package removed), and <strong>Emergency Alerts</strong> (SOS triggered or situation escalated to law enforcement).
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">
                    <h3>Does RADCam work outdoors?</h3>
                    <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                </button>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                        Yes. RADCam's weather-resistant housing is designed for both indoor and outdoor deployment. It performs in rain, heat, cold, and low-light conditions. Mount it at your front door, garage, driveway, backyard, anywhere you need intelligent coverage.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">
                    <h3>When does the subscription start?</h3>
                    <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                </button>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                        Your RADCam subscription is activated after the hardware is received and the camera is set up through the mobile app. You won't be charged until you've completed the activation process, so you can take your time getting it installed.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">
                    <h3>How is RADCam different from Ring or Nest?</h3>
                    <span class="faq-icon">+</span>
                </button>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                    <div class="faq-answer-inner">
                        Ring and Nest record what happens. RADCam responds to what's happening, in real time, autonomously, without you needing to intervene. It's built on the same enterprise AI platform that secures Fortune 500 campuses and government facilities. The core difference: RADCam is an active security responder, not a passive recording device.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

